00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.500
Welcome to episode 21 of the MJS Packaging podcast.

00:00:07.500 --> 00:00:18.300
Today I am joined by Dr Lena Weiss, who runs cold-chain qualification at a top-five biopharma. Lena, welcome.

00:00:18.300 --> 00:00:22.100
Thanks, glad to be here.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:31.400
Why borosilicate Type I is still the default for biologics. The honest answer is that the alternatives still trade at a quality risk we are not willing to take for an injectable program at minus eighty.

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:48.200
Glass is well-characterised, the supply chain is mature, and the failure modes are known.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:47.700
What fails first when a vial is cycled too aggressively. The closure usually moves before the glass does. You will see torque drift, then liner deformation, and only then any glass effect.

00:02:47.700 --> 00:03:05.300
Designing the stability protocol to catch closure movement at the first time-point is what separates a clean qualification from a noisy one.
